The article discusses the urgent health crisis in the United States, which is the rising prevalence of diet-related diseases such as type 2 diabetes, obesity, hypertension, and certain cancers. These diseases disproportionately impact historically underserved communities. The Biden-Harris Administration aims to address this crisis and end hunger by 2030 through transformative programs, policies, and system changes. The strategy includes five pillars and calls for collective action from the federal government, private sector, state and local governments, academia, and nonprofit and community groups. The article emphasizes that progress requires sustained action and mobilization from every segment of society.